The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Saturday, July 24, 2004  Corporate Briefs																								 Bright Star Investments Pvt Ltd, an investment management outfit, has acquired an additional 2.01 per cent stake in VST Industries Ltd, taking its total holding in the Hyderabad-based company to 23.58 per cent. Bright star acquired 3.10 lakh shares from the market on July 19, the company informed the Bombay Stock Exchange.																								 South Korea-based LG Electronics will raise equity in its Indian software arm LG Soft to 89 per cent from 70 per cent at present, following a government approval for a transfer of 14 per cent of the paid-up capital of its Indian unit from IL amp;FS trust company.																								 Indian Overseas Bank (IOB) will soon decide on diluting its strategic stake in Thailand-based Bharat Overseas Bank. We will soon take a view on whether we will have to dilute our 30 per cent holding in Bharat Overseas to comply with RBI guidelines, chairman and managing director S. C. Gupta said.																								 The UK has emerged as the top European investment destination for Indian companies, whose number has increased by 47 per cent in 2003-04 over last year. 																								 Allahabad Bank has signed a memorandum of understanding with Greaves Cotton Ltd for financing farm machinery of the latter to the farmers.																								 The Indo-American Chamber of Commerce and the Federation of Indian Export Organisations (FIEO) have jointly organised a seminar on the emerging opportunities in agriculture with focus on Indo-US business on July 27 in Calcutta. ADVERTISEMENT
